    "creation_date" : 1453100668,
    "answer_id" : 34848945,
    "question_id" : 5683206,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Java 7 introduced <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/concurrent/ThreadLocalRandom.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">ThreadLocalRandom</a> which is <strong><em>isolated to the current thread</em></strong>.</p>\n\n<p>This is an another rendition of <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/a/5683221/330457\">maerics's solution</a>.</p>\n\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>final byte[] bytes = new byte[20];\nThreadLocalRandom.current().nextBytes(bytes);\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 2203460,
      "reputation" : 7052,
      "user_id" : 1947251,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 86,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/8cLuB.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "DavidR",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1947251/davidr"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 70,
    "last_activity_date" : 1661555984,
    "last_edit_date" : 1661555984,
    "creation_date" : 1453332271,
    "answer_id" : 34912596,
    "question_id" : 5683206,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>If you want a cryptographically strong random number generator (also thread safe) without using a third party API, you can use <code>SecureRandom</code>.</p>\n<p>Java 8 (more secure than previous versions):</p>\n<pre><code>byte[] bytes = new byte[20];\nSecureRandom.getInstanceStrong().nextBytes(bytes);\n</code></pre>\n<p>Java 6 &amp; 7:</p>\n<pre><code>SecureRandom random = new SecureRandom();\nbyte[] bytes = new byte[20];\nrandom.nextBytes(bytes);\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 2203460,
        "reputation" : 7052,
        "user_id" : 1947251,
